{{coi|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox website | name = Alison | logo = File:Alison-logo-wikipedia.png | screenshot = | caption = | url = {{URL|https://alison.com/}} | type = [[Online education]] | language = English, [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[French language|French]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Russian language|Russian]]. [[Arabic]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]] | registration = Required | owner = Private | author = Mike Feerick, founder and CEO | launch date = April 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ALISON.com |title=Free Online Courses, Workplace Skills Training, Interactive Education and Multimedia Learning |publisher=ALISON |accessdate=2013-07-31}}</ref> | alexa = 7,950 Global }}'''Alison''' is an [[e-learning]] provider founded in [[Galway]], Ireland in 2007 by [[Mike Feerick]].<ref name=WIRED>{{cite web|last=Glader|first=Paul|title=Khan Academy Competitor? Mike Feerick of ALISON.com Talks About The Future Of Online Education|url=http://www.wiredacademic.com/2011/09/khan-academy-competitor-mike-feerick-of-alison-com-talks-about-future-of-online-education/#sthash.bQYwAbYq.dpuf|work=Wired Academic|publisher=Wired Academic|accessdate=25 July 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531031705/http://www.wiredacademic.com/2011/09/khan-academy-competitor-mike-feerick-of-alison-com-talks-about-future-of-online-education/#sthash.bQYwAbYq.dpuf|archivedate=31 May 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name="Information Week">{{cite news|last=Booker|first=Ellis|title=Early MOOC Takes A Different Path|url=http://www.informationweek.co.uk/education/online-learning/early-mooc-takes-a-different-path/240147364|accessdate=25 July 2013|newspaper=Information Week|date=January 30, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130616060234/http://www.informationweek.co.uk/education/online-learning/early-mooc-takes-a-different-path/240147364|archivedate=16 June 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name="NYTIMES">{{cite news|last=Bornstein|first=David|title=Open Education For A Global Economy|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/11/open-education-for-a-global-economy/?_r=0|accessdate=25 July 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name="forbes.com">https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterhigh/2017/12/11/is-alison-the-answer-to-the-worlds-education-needs/#4fd0594f5e4b</ref> As of December 2017, Alison had 11 million registered learners, 1.5 million graduates, and 1,000 courses available for free access.<ref name="forbes.com"/> Alison's learners have access to courses published by institutions like [[Columbia University]], [[Cambridge University]], [[Yale University]], and companies such as [[Microsoft]] and [[Google]].<ref name=NEWSDAY>{{cite news|last=Goldmark|first=Peter|title=A Website That Lifts People Up|url=http://www.newsday.com/opinion/oped/goldmark-a-website-that-lifts-people-up-1.3798996|accessdate=25 July 2013|newspaper=Newsday|date=June 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name=IRISHTIMES>{{cite news|last=Holden|first=Louise|title=Special Report — Ashoka 'Change Nation'|newspaper=Irish Times|date=March 21, 2012}}</ref>
==Business model== Alison invites publishers to put some of their courses on the platform, some who wish do to so for no monetary return, others in turn agree to provide their content for free on Alison's website due to the shared revenue gleaned 'mostly from advertising and sales of certificates.'<ref name="NYTIMES"/> According to [[The Economist]], the company seeks to drive education through advertising in the manner of television and radio.<ref name=ECONOMIST>{{cite news|title=The Attack Of The MOOCs|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business/21582001-army-new-online-courses-scaring-wits-out-traditional-universities-can-they|accessdate=26 July 2013|newspaper=The Economist|date=July 20, 2013}}</ref> Through the online [[pay per click]] advertising revenue model, Alison has founded a business model whereby "learners in the developed countries are essentially paying for those in developing countries" while providing the learning materials for free.<ref name="WIRED"/>
==Courses== Alison currently offers over 1000 courses across certificate and diploma level in ten languages.<ref name="Information Week" /> The certificate level courses necessitate 1–2 hours study with the more rigorous diploma level offerings requiring 9–11 hours study on the part of the learner.<ref name=NYTIMES /> Alison note on their website that "there is no time limit on completing a course, so learners can study entirely at their own pace" and that some of the courses such as the [[Microsoft]] [[Digital Literacy]] Program may take up to 20 hours to complete.<ref name="ALISON HELP 2">{{cite web|title=How Long Do Courses Take to Complete?|url=http://alison.com/knowledgebase/entry/49/|work=ALISON: help|publisher=ALISON|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> One of Alison's courses named ABC IT, a 15–20 hour training suite, is cited by the [[New York Times]] as "covering similar ground" to the [[International Computer Driving License]] without the cost of certification.<ref name=NYTIMES />
==Reception== David Bornstein noted that "practical skills training is usually expensive".<ref name=NYTIMES /> Some have argued for the ineffectiveness of the [[MOOC]] model of this kind in delivering real educational impact, highlighting the lack of personal interaction with educators and the high drop-out rate of users with no incentive to commit without any material investment of their own.<ref name=SLATE>{{cite web|last=Rees|first=Jonathan|title=The MOOC Racket|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/future_tense/2013/07/moocs_could_be_disastrous_for_students_and_professors.html|work=Future Tense: The Slate|publisher=The Slate Group|accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref>
Other sources have noted the "sustainable" manner of Alison's operating procedure, [[The Economist]] suggesting that Alison generates "plenty of revenue" on its website while still providing its learning materials of "mostly vocational education" for free.<ref name=ECONOMIST />
